<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>down and out • up and out</xh5><p> <i>down and out—</i>1. said of a person without means of livelihood: “You’ve never been <u>down and out</u>, I imagine, Mr. Forsyte?” “No,” answered Soames. <i>2. (of business, etc.)</i> lacking resources or prospects: The local housing industry is <u>down and out</u>. <i>Cf.: down but not out</i>—said of smb. who is down on his luck or suffered a serious setback but feels hopeful: Though analysts feel that Khin Nyunt is <u>down but not out</u>, as of now the chances of his return to power are not bright.</p><p><i>up and out</i>—(UK) convalescent; no longer in bed: There was Phyllis to help me recoup and now I am <u>up and out</u> again getting into trouble just like before.</p> </entry>
